<font color="#FF0000">WES COOLEY &amp; SPECIAL FORCES</font><br>
<tt>Thu Dec 19 12:58:55 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
The interesting thing about ex-U.S. Representative Wes Cooley is that he claims to have been in the Army Special Forces, during the Korean War.  He's now &quot;pleaded not guilty to charges of lying in the state Voters' Pamphlet&quot; according to The Oregonian newspaper on Dec. 17, 1996.  <br><br>
&quot;The first-term House member was in the Special Forces during the Korean War. But no available military records validate his claims to have fought overseas. The 2nd District Republican was indicted last Tuesday on the state charges, each of which caries a maximum penalty of five years in prison and a $100,000 fine. If convicted, Cooley probably would serve no more than 90 days under state sentencing guidelines.&quot; (Bryan Denson of The Oregonian staff)<br><br>
What I find intriguing is that, while there probably were special operations during Korea, I don't think there was a Special Forces in any of the services until the 1960's.  Didn't President Kennedy establish the Special Forces?  This would be well after the conclusion of the Korean War.
